## Parallelization — two flavors: sectioning and voting
direction: down

intro: {
  shape: text
  label: "Run multiple LLM calls IN PARALLEL.\nTwo distinct shapes, very different uses:"
  style.italic: true
  style.bold: true
  style.font-color: "#7c3aed"
}

sectioning: {
  label: "SECTIONING\n(decompose into independent subtasks)"
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#dbeafe"
  style.stroke: "#2563eb"
  body: {label: "Split work into N independent parts.\nEach part runs as its own LLM call.\nAggregate results at the end.\n\nExamples:\n• Translate K paragraphs in parallel\n• Analyze K files of a repo at once\n• Generate K sections of a report"; shape: text}
}

voting: {
  label: "VOTING\n(same task, K times, aggregate)"
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#bbf7d0"
  style.stroke: "#16a34a"
  body: {label: "Run the SAME task K times at temperature.\nAggregate via majority vote / averaging /\nbest-of-K selection.\n\nExamples:\n• Self-Consistency for reasoning\n• Multiple safety checks per output\n• Best-of-N for generation"; shape: text}
}

merge: {
  label: "Aggregation step\n(reduce K outputs → 1)"
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#fde68a"
  style.stroke: "#d97706"
  body: {label: "Sectioning: stitch back together\nVoting: pick majority / average / best"; shape: text}
}

note: {
  shape: text
  label: "Both improve quality. Both cost K× the tokens.\nSectioning improves SCALE; voting improves RELIABILITY."
  style.italic: true
  style.font-color: "#7c3aed"
}

intro -> sectioning
intro -> voting
sectioning -> merge
voting -> merge
merge -> note
